.\" Manual page for _Holberton_shell project
.\" Last update: 29-04-2023
.TH _SHELL 1 "29 Apr 2023" "version 1.0" "_simple_shell man page"
.SH NAME
hsh - Holberton Simple SHell
.SH SYNOPSIS
hsh [options] [command_string | file]
.SH DESCRIPTION
hsh is a simple command interpreter taking as a reference the UNIX shell.
.TP
A command line interpreter is a program that allows the entering of commands and then executes those commands to the operating system.
.SH INSTALLATION
To use this Simple Shell (called hsh) follow these steps:
.TP
1. Clone this repository to your local environment.
.TP
git clone https://github.com/Hiojam/holbertonschool-simple_shell.git
.TP
2. Go to the holbertonschool-simple_shell directory.
.TP
cd holbertonschool-simple_shell/
.TP
3. Compile the C source code using this command:
.TP
$ gcc -g -Wall -Werror -Wextra -pedantic -std=gnu89 *.c -o hsh
.SH NORMAL COMMANDS
It is possible to execute any command present in the directory /usr/bin/
.TP
For example:
.TP
pwd - print name of current/working directory
.TP
/root/holbertonschool-simple_shell$ pwd
.TP
/root/holbertonschool-simple_shell

.SH BUILT-IN COMMANDS
A built-in command is a command or function that is part of the shell itself. The command is "built-in" to the shell program — no external program is necessary to run the command, and a new process does not need to be created.
.TP
The following built-in commands are supported:
.TP
clear: Clear the terminal screen
.TP
cd:  Change the working directory
.TP
alias: Define or display aliases
.TP
history: Log the hsh command history
.TP
exit: Exit from the shell
.TP
help: Show information about built-int commands
.TP
env: print environment variables
.TP
setenv: Change or add an environment variable
.TP
unsetenv: Unset values of environment variables
